# 53_actions_edit_smoke — Tier 2 m3 Edit-menu sweep (s255).
# Validates the six additional Edit-menu actions migrated from raw
# `add_action` to `add_scripted_action`: cut / copy / paste / duplicate
# / delete-selected / duplicate-in-place. Sibling smoke to 52, same
# conservative-shape posture: verb-presence + invocation-no-throw +
# refusal coverage.
#
# **Why conservative.** None of the six Edit verbs has a scriptable
# observable today. Clipboard contents aren't exposed (future `clip`
# singleton territory; bucket C item `win.view-clipboard` is the
# launcher-equivalent for the human-readable variant). Selection
# count isn't exposed on `objects` yet (would help test
# delete-selected / duplicate / duplicate-in-place). Per the handoff,
# the wrap-now plumbing was proved at m2; m3 widens the batch on the
# same proven plumbing. Trace channel: invocations land cleanly (no
# `error invoke threw:` lines). Visual channel: Scott confirms menu
# Edit ▸ Cut / Copy / Paste / Duplicate / Duplicate in Place / Delete
# still behave identically.
#
# ── What this smoke exercises ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Nine observables across the wrapper-side surface:
#
#   Phase 1: `list` — confirm `win` is still registered (sanity-check;
#            m2 already validated this, but the smoke is the wrap-now
#            batch's own test, so it re-confirms instead of assuming).
#
#   Phases 2-7: each of the six new wrap-now verbs invoked once.
#            Operator-visual on each `ok` echo. Negative case for any
#            phase: `error invoke threw: win <verb>: unknown verb`
#            means the helper's register_action() never landed for that
#            verb (the m3 migration site is broken).
#
#            Each invoke fires the underlying Gio action's callback.
#            Side effects ARE present at the canvas layer (cut empties
#            selection AND populates clipboard; paste round-trips
#            clipboard content back; duplicate inserts a new node;
#            delete-selected removes the selection; duplicate-in-place
#            zero-offsets it) — none assertable from script today.
#            Scott's visual channel is the second axis of evidence.
#
#   Phases 8-9: refusal coverage, parallel to smoke 52's last two phases.
#            Confirms the wrapper still refuses unknown verbs and
#            argument-bearing invocations of parameterless verbs. The
#            refusals are wrapper-wide invariants, not per-verb, so
#            one of each is sufficient — but re-exercising them in
#            each Tier 2 smoke prevents drift if the invoke() body
#            ever loses the refusal branches.
#
# ── Caller context ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Runs through ScripterWindow's listener, m_context = RunContext::Scripter.
# All six m3-batch verbs declare their mask as Scripter | TestRunner per
# the wrap-now posture. Macro is OUT — see smoke 52's preamble for the
# rationale (clipboard verbs in a macro replay would interact with the
# user's actual system clipboard, which the Macro context is not
# permissioned to do).
#
# ── Test isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke MUTATES canvas state via the six Edit verbs. The mutations,
# in order, are designed to leave the canvas in approximately the same
# state it started in:
#
#   - `win cut` — clipboard <- current selection; selection removed.
#                 **If selection is empty, no-op.** Doesn't throw.
#   - `win copy` — clipboard <- current selection (no removal).
#                 **No-op on empty selection.**
#   - `win paste` — selection <- clipboard contents at offset. After
#                 the preceding cut+copy, the clipboard holds the
#                 cut-set; this round-trips it back onto the canvas.
#                 Net effect of cut+paste: selection content moves by
#                 the paste offset (intended behaviour of Cut+Paste).
#   - `win duplicate` — selection duplicated at offset. Inserts new
#                 nodes adjacent to original selection.
#   - `win delete-selected` — removes everything currently selected.
#                 After `duplicate`, selection is the new copies; this
#                 deletes them, undoing the duplicate's structural
#                 effect. The cut+paste offset remains.
#   - `win duplicate-in-place` — zero-offset duplicate. After
#                 delete-selected the selection is empty (delete
#                 clears it as a side effect), so this is a no-op.
#
# After the smoke runs:
#   - Canvas content has shifted by the paste offset (cut+paste is
#     net = move-by-offset). NOT idempotent; running twice doubles
#     the shift. Scott may want to ⌘Z a few times to restore.
#   - The actual clipboard content holds whatever was last cut/copied.
#     If Scott had something else there before, it's overwritten.
#
# This is the conservative-isolation posture: each verb fires, the
# net state mutation is small and easily undone via ⌘Z. The smoke is
# safe to run repeatedly but not perfectly idempotent — flagged here
# so the visual channel knows to expect a small content shift after
# the run.
#
# ── Precondition reminders ────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This smoke assumes:
#   1. Curvz is running with at least one project + one document open.
#   2. The active doc has at least one object selected (or selectable;
#      the smoke does not auto-select before cut, so the clipboard
#      verbs no-op cleanly on empty selection — but selecting something
#      first makes the visual channel legible).
#
# Pre-run setup (recommended): in the canvas, drag-select one or two
# small objects so cut / copy / paste / duplicate / delete-selected /
# duplicate-in-place all have content to act on.

#[sub] === Phase 1: registry sanity-check — `win` is still registered ===

#[sub] Re-confirms the m2 plumbing didn't regress. Should be redundant
#[sub] with smoke 52 phase 1, but Tier 2 smokes are self-contained.

list

#[sub] === Phase 2: cut verb is addressable ===

#[sub] First m3-batch verb. Invoke; no error means the helper
#[sub] registered the action. Calls m_canvas.cut_selected();
#[sub] visual: current selection vanishes (moves to clipboard).
#[sub]
#[sub] Negative case: `error invoke threw: win cut: unknown verb`
#[sub] means register_action() never landed.

win cut

#[sub] === Phase 3: copy verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Second m3-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.copy_selected(); visual:
#[sub] nothing visible changes (copy is silent on the canvas; clipboard
#[sub] is the affected substrate).

win copy

#[sub] === Phase 4: paste verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Third m3-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.paste_clipboard(); visual:
#[sub] the cut content (from phase 2's clipboard payload) reappears
#[sub] on canvas at the paste offset.

win paste

#[sub] === Phase 5: duplicate verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Fourth m3-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.duplicate_selected();
#[sub] visual: selection content appears twice (original + offset
#[sub] copy). Distinct from `objects.duplicate "name"` (per audit
#[sub] fork 1): this operates on current selection, not a named
#[sub] object.

win duplicate

#[sub] === Phase 6: delete-selected verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Fifth m3-batch verb. Calls m_canvas.delete_selected(); visual:
#[sub] the just-duplicated copies vanish. Distinct from
#[sub] `objects.delete <name>` (per audit fork 2).

win delete-selected

#[sub] === Phase 7: duplicate-in-place verb is addressable ===

#[sub] Sixth and final m3-batch verb. Calls
#[sub] m_canvas.duplicate_in_place_selected(); visual: zero-offset
#[sub] duplicate (the new copies overlap the originals). After
#[sub] delete-selected cleared the selection, this is effectively
#[sub] a no-op on empty selection — invocation still lands cleanly
#[sub] at the wrapper layer.

win duplicate-in-place

#[sub] === Phase 8: unknown-verb refusal ===

#[sub] Same refusal smoke as 52 phase 7 — confirms the wrapper still
#[sub] rejects verbs outside the wrap-now subset. `win quit` is bucket
#[sub] C (future `app.quit` singleton); real Gio action but NOT in the
#[sub] wrapper's verb surface.

win quit

#[sub] === Phase 9: extra-argument refusal ===

#[sub] Parallel to 52 phase 8. All six m3-batch verbs are parameterless;
#[sub] passing an argument should refuse. `win cut "argument"` exercises
#[sub] the invoke() body's args-empty check on one of the new verbs
#[sub] (52 used `win undo`).

win cut "argument"

